body:
Here's an example; I started with html_full.tpl, deleted this section:

```
{% for css in resources.inlining.css -%}
    <style type="text/css">
    {{ css }}
    </style>
{% endfor %}
```

which pulls in the 200K of CSS junk, and then manually pulled in whatever short CSS seemed to make the output look OK. Resulting template is [here on github gist](https://gist.github.com/jason-s/ebcf84479ebb1db5c866), which adds about 7K of CSS. This is a totally ad-hoc hack that worked for me and I'm only showing it as an example of what I'm talking about.

> Can you work out what CSS is actually unnecessary in there? It may be that we're erroneously shipping CSS that exported notebooks never use. On the other hand, 200 KB is practically nothing to send around nowadays, so I don't think we want to start refactoring the HTML and CSS to trim it 

I'm not sure, I'll take a look at it. I was going to guess that it's the syntax highlighting, but it looks like it's just the oodles of rules. It's not that it's "unnecessary" to match the behavior of IPython. It's that it's full of small details, each of which have very little effect. So if you want the exact look of IPython, it's all necessary. If you want a first-order approximation, most of it isn't. 

200KB generated once is nothing at all. 200kB generated repeatedly starts to add up.... when you're traveling internationally and have to download 20MB of email messages, you become more sensitive to this.

